<DOCID> nyt960709.0802 </DOCID>
<STORYID cat=w pri=r> A8813 </STORYID>
<SLUG fv=ttx-z> BC-ICING-CRASH-TEX </SLUG>
<DATE> <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">07-09</TIMEX> </DATE>
<NWORDS> 0542 </NWORDS>
<PREAMBLE>
BC-ICING-CRASH-TEX
PLANE MAKER DIDN'T WARN OF ICING DANGER, REPORT SAYS
(For use by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NYTimes News Service</ENAMEX> clients)
By <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">MICHAEL D. TOWLE</ENAMEX>
c.<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">1996</TIMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Fort Worth Star-Telegram</ENAMEX>
</PREAMBLE>
<TEXT>
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">WASHINGTON</ENAMEX>  &MD;  The deadly crash of an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Eagle</ENAMEX> flight near
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Roselawn</ENAMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Ind.</ENAMEX>, in <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">October 1994</TIMEX> may have been prevented had a
French aircraft manufacturer cautioned <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">U.S.</ENAMEX> officials on the
dangers of flying the plane in icy weather, federal investigators
said <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">Tuesday</TIMEX>.
<p>
   Concluding a <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">20-month</TIMEX> investigation into the crash of the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Eagle</ENAMEX> ATR-72, which killed all 68 people aboard, the
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">National Transportation Safety Board</ENAMEX> also faulted the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Directorate
General for Civil Aviation</ENAMEX>, a French agency similar to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Federal
Aviation Administration</ENAMEX>, for not alerting airliners to the dangers.
<p>
   Investigators found that the ``probable cause'' of the crash was
the accumulation of ice on the wings of the turboprop aircraft,
which caused it to roll out of control and crash.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX> said aircraft maker <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Avions de Transport Regional</ENAMEX>, or
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ATR</ENAMEX>, failed to disclose ``adequate information'' concerning the
severe effect that freezing rain would have on control of its
aircraft. The board also said that the French aviation agency
failed to take action to prevent ATR-72 mishaps in icy conditions
and that it also did not provide warnings.
<p>
   ``The real concern to me in this report was that the flight crew
did not have the level of information that other individuals in the
system had in regards to possible performance problems with the
aircraft,'' <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX> Chairman <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Jim Hall</ENAMEX> said.
<p>
   The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX> board also found that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> could have done a better
job of overseeing <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ATR</ENAMEX> aircraft in the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">United States</ENAMEX>. The board
recommended that the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">FAA</ENAMEX> begin asking all manufacturers to provide
information about ``unsafe characteristics of flight'' to the
agency before aircraft are certified.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ATR</ENAMEX> officials said the company ``strongly'' disagrees with the
``inaccurate presentation made by the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX>.'' The company, in a
statement issued to reporters, said the report was ``incomplete and
focused on only some of the factors that contributed to the
accident.''
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ATR</ENAMEX> said the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX> ignored the fact that the plane was flown for
more than 30 minutes in icy weather, ``well outside the aircraft
certification envelope.''
<p>
   At the time of the crash, the plane was in a holding pattern
over <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION" MIN="Indiana">northwest Indiana</ENAMEX>, waiting to land at <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Chicago</ENAMEX>'s <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">O'Hare
International Airport</ENAMEX>. Radar showed that the flight was operating
in light to moderate icing, but the pilots did not report any
problems.
<p>
   <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Charles Pereira</ENAMEX>, an <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">NTSB</ENAMEX> investigator, said that on five other
occasions <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ATR</ENAMEX> aircraft had encountered icing problems serious
enough to cause sudden rolls during flight. He said pilots were
able to recover in those cases, but he criticized <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ATR</ENAMEX> for not
issuing written guidelines for flying in cold, icy weather
afterward.
<p>
   The board made several recommendations for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Eagle</ENAMEX>, a
unit of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Fort Worth</ENAMEX>-based <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">American Airlines</ENAMEX>. It said the airline
should:
<p>
    &MD;  Give flight crews more information about weather on routes
they will fly.
<p>
    &MD;  Encourage flight crews to concentrate solely on flight matters
in icy conditions.
<p>
    &MD;  Eliminate any conflicts in guidance and procedures in
published manuals.
</TEXT>
